<!-- ── WHAT IS A PEO ── -->
<section class="section bg-white">
  <div class="container" style="max-width:840px;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:20px;">What is a PEO?</h2>
    <p class="lead" style="margin-bottom:24px;">A Professional Employer Organization is a company that co-employs your workforce. They become the employer of record for administrative purposes — handling payroll, taxes, benefits, workers comp, and HR compliance — while you retain full control of your business operations.</p>
    <p style="margin-bottom:24px;">The co-employment arrangement allows the PEO to pool your employees with thousands of others, which gives your business access to Fortune 500-level benefits at a fraction of the cost it would take to build that infrastructure independently.</p>
    <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:24px;">
      <p><strong>The short version:</strong> You run your business. They run the back-office HR. You get enterprise-grade benefits and compliance support. You pay a fee per employee per month — and in most cases, the savings on benefits and risk management more than offset the cost.</p>
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin: 40px 0 16px;">What does a PEO actually cover?</h3>
    <div class="card-grid card-grid-2" style="margin-bottom:40px;">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">💰</div>
        <h3>Payroll & Tax Administration</h3>
        <p>Processing payroll, managing tax withholdings, filing W-2s, handling garnishments and deductions. The PEO takes on significant payroll tax liability as a co-employer.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">🏥</div>
        <h3>Employee Benefits</h3>
        <p>Health, dental, vision, life, and disability insurance — typically at rates a small employer could never negotiate independently. Many PEOs also offer 401(k), HSA, and FSA plans.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">🦺</div>
        <h3>Workers Compensation</h3>
        <p>Coverage under the PEO's master policy, often at better rates than a small employer qualifies for. Claims management, safety programs, and return-to-work coordination.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">⚖️</div>
        <h3>HR Compliance & Support</h3>
        <p>Employee handbook development, EPLI coverage, ACA compliance, I-9 administration, multi-state employment law guidance, and HR advisory on employee relations issues.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">🖥️</div>
        <h3>HR Technology</h3>
        <p>Online onboarding, time and attendance tracking, benefits enrollment portals, PTO management, and employee self-service tools — typically included in the PEO fee.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-icon">📋</div>
        <h3>Risk Management</h3>
        <p>Unemployment claims management, OSHA assistance, workplace safety programs, and shared employer practices liability — reducing your exposure across multiple risk categories.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin: 40px 0 16px;">How is PEO pricing structured?</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:16px;">PEOs typically use one of two pricing models:</p>

    <div class="card-grid card-grid-2" style="margin-bottom:32px;">
      <div class="card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--navy);">
        <h3 style="color:var(--navy);">PEPM — Per Employee Per Month</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom:12px;">A flat monthly fee per employee. Common range: <strong>$100 to $250 per employee per month</strong>, depending on company size, industry, and services included.</p>
        <p style="font-size:.9rem;"><strong>Best for:</strong> Businesses where pricing predictability matters. Easier to budget and model.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--teal);">
        <h3 style="color:var(--teal);">% of Gross Payroll</h3>
        <p style="margin-bottom:12px;">A percentage of your total payroll. Common range: <strong>2% to 12%</strong>, depending on the same factors.</p>
        <p style="font-size:.9rem;"><strong>Best for:</strong> Businesses with variable payroll. Cost scales with your team's compensation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:40px;">
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> These are administrator fees only. Benefits costs are typically separate and pass through at the negotiated group rate. An experienced advisor can tell you exactly what your all-in cost should look like before you talk to a single PEO.</p>
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin: 40px 0 16px;">What is a CPEO?</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:16px;">A Certified Professional Employer Organization (CPEO) has been certified by the IRS, meeting specific financial and operational standards. CPEO status matters for two reasons:</p>
    <ul class="checklist" style="margin-bottom:32px;">
      <li>Cleaner treatment of certain payroll tax liabilities — the CPEO takes on the liability from the beginning of the calendar year, not just from the date you start.</li>
      <li>Signals financial stability and operational discipline. Not all PEOs pursue CPEO status, but it is a meaningful credential to look for.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 style="margin: 40px 0 16px;">PEO vs. ASO vs. EOR — what is the difference?</h3>
    <table class="compare-table" style="margin-bottom:32px;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="background:var(--gray-100); color:var(--gray-600);">Model</th>
          <th class="good">PEO</th>
          <th style="background:var(--teal); color:white;">ASO</th>
          <th style="background:var(--gray-600); color:white;">EOR</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Co-employment</strong></td>
          <td class="good-cell">Yes — shared employer of record</td>
          <td>No — you remain sole employer</td>
          <td>Yes — EOR is the legal employer</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Best for</strong></td>
          <td>5-150 employee US-based businesses</td>
          <td>Businesses that want admin help without co-employment</td>
          <td>Hiring in countries where you have no legal entity</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Benefits pooling</strong></td>
          <td class="good-cell">Yes — group purchasing power</td>
          <td>Limited</td>
          <td>Yes, but at EOR's rates</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Typical cost</strong></td>
          <td>$100-250 PEPM or 2-12% payroll</td>
          <td>$50-150 PEPM</td>
          <td>$500-2,500+ PEPM</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin: 40px 0 16px;">Is a PEO right for your business?</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:16px;">A PEO tends to make the most sense when three or more of these apply:</p>
    <ul class="checklist" style="margin-bottom:32px;">
      <li>You have between 5 and 150 employees</li>
      <li>You or a non-HR person is handling payroll and HR administration</li>
      <li>You are losing candidates because your benefits cannot compete with larger employers</li>
      <li>You have workers comp exposure and your rates have increased</li>
      <li>You are growing and adding employees in new states</li>
      <li>You have had an employment-related complaint or compliance issue in the past two years</li>
      <li>You are spending meaningful time on HR tasks that are not your core business</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

